To find the value of the expression $2^{-1} + 2^{-2} + 2^{-3} + 2^{-4} + 2^{-5} + 2^{-6}$ modulo $13$, we can first rewrite the expression in terms of a single geometric series:

\begin{align*}
2^{-1} + 2^{-2} + 2^{-3} + 2^{-4} + 2^{-5} + 2^{-6} &= \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{2^2} + \frac{1}{2^3} + \frac{1}{2^4} + \frac{1}{2^5} + \frac{1}{2^6} \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \left(1 + \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{2^2} + \frac{1}{2^3} + \frac{1}{2^4} + \frac{1}{2^5}\right) \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \left(\frac{1 - \frac{1}{2^6}}{1 - \frac{1}{2}}\right) \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \left(\frac{1 - \frac{1}{64}}{\frac{1}{2}}\right) \\
&= \frac{63}{64} \\
&= \frac{63}{64} \equiv \frac{-1}{64} \equiv \frac{-1}{-1} \equiv 1 \pmod{13}
\end{align*}

Therefore, the value of the expression $2^{-1} + 2^{-2} + 2^{-3} + 2^{-4} + 2^{-5} + 2^{-6}$ modulo $13$ is $\boxed{1}$.

